While early statements were rarely more than 300-400 words, in the post GFC era, the length of each statement became progressively longer.  https://t.co/5XF54tsiNh  https://t.co/bhEo1okhuD
A key responsibility of the Fed is to keep inflation levels stable, but controlling â€˜inflationâ€™ in its policy statements hasnâ€™t been a focus over the years.

As far back as 1975, a US citizen actually sued the FOMC under the FOIA act demanding that the committee release its policy decisions following the meeting, but the FOMC argued that doing so would give speculators an unfair advantage.

While the term â€˜Fed-watchersâ€™ today generally refers to media reporters who cover the Fed, before the Fed communicated what actions they were taking, analysts at each of the investment banks would watch their activity at the open market desk to try and figure it out.
Ultimately, it was agreed that meeting decisions would be released on a delayed basis after the following meeting.  https://t.co/wMxnD62UGF
Beginning in 1995, the FOMC only issued statements after meetings in which it would change rates, and it wasnâ€™t until May 1999 that the Fed started releasing statements after every meeting.

With all the attention focused on the Fed and its meetings these days, one might be surprised to learn that prior to 1994, the FOMC didnâ€™t issue policy statements right after its meetings, and the markets were forced to figure it out based on the moves of the open market desk.

After the stock market crash of 1987, the Fed released the following statement: â€œThe Federal Reserve, consistent with its responsibilities as the nationâ€™s central bank, affirmed today its readiness to serve as a source of liquidity to support the economic and financial system.â€

After WWII, the Employment Act required that the Fed have a goal of achieving maximum employment. In 1956, the Bank Holding Company Act further added to Fed responsibilities, making it the regulator of multi-bank holding companies.

The responsibilities of the Fed have expanded exponentially since its creation, and it is now expected to use monetary policy to provide support to markets whenever trouble arises. In 1935, the Federal Open Market Committee was created, allowing for more effective action.

Since its creation, the Fed was expected to be nimble and react to the needs of the country. 16 years after its creation, the Fed was blamed by many for not curtailing the speculative excesses of the late 1920s on Wall Street that eventually led to the Great Depression.
By this time, there was general consensus that a central bank was needed to ensure the health of the banking system.  https://t.co/sTn7jccaHY

The Federal Reserve was created to â€œfurnish an elastic currency, to afford means of rediscounting commercial paper, to establish a more effective supervision of banking in the United States, and for other purposes.â€  https://t.co/SwVcVi1riC

This created the regional federal reserve system which designated 8-12 cities to host their regional Feds, each one overseeing a unique geographical area.  https://t.co/ZdXGfo95bs  https://t.co/PChiFDLtAE
The need for a decentralized central bank became apparent after the panic of 1907, in which speculation led to a run on banks. The run forced JP Morgan to take action to avoid national disaster.
The final iteration of the Act was far different than the original proposal. President Wilson advocated for a regional Fed system that was overseen by a supervisory board in DC.

On this day in 1913, President Woodrow Wilson signed the Federal Reserve Act into law officially establishing â€˜the Fedâ€™. The act was initially proposed by Congressmen Carter Glass and Senator Robert Owen.

On top of this, the USMCA essentially shielded US corporations from liability for digital content in Mexico and Canada and prohibited the two countries from forcing US corporations to store data in their nations.
The USMCA also strengthened labor laws in Mexico, gave US dairy farmers better access to the international market, and established certain environmental protections.

The largest economic focus of the USMCA revolved around autos. The deal requires 75% of automotive components to be manufactured in one of the three participating countries. Additionally, more vehicle parts were required to be manufactured by workers who earned at least $16/hour.

Although the USMCA did not deliver on all campaign promises made by the former President, such as 35% auto tariffs on vehicles and parts manufactured in Mexico, the deal did make a few material changes to the previous agreement.

Critics of NAFTA argued that it hurt American workers as corporations moved manufacturing facilities to Mexico, where wages were much lower. Conversely, smaller Mexican farms were hurt when forced to compete with American agribusinesses.   https://t.co/8NggIq9lWI
In 2017, about $90 billion of oil was imported from the two nations. For the US, importing from these two nations was far more favorable than importing from Iran and Venezuela.
The long-term impacts of NAFTA were generally mixed and depend on your perspective.  While the US lost manufacturing jobs, cheaper imports helped keep downward pressure on prices

During his campaign, President Trump commented that NAFTA was â€œthe worst trade deal ever made,â€ citing wage suppression and a loss of manufacturing jobs. During his Presidency, Trump replaced NAFTA with the US-Mexico-Canada Agreement (USMCA).  https://t.co/QZ3wIyVRt7
NAFTA also decreased the price of oil for the US, but these specific positive impacts declined in the last few years as oil production in the US ramped up.  https://t.co/kICsBv1pei

From 1993 to 2019, trade between participating members increased more than 4-fold to $1.23T. US exports to Mexico and Canada increased by almost 4x. Just over a quarter of US imports came from the two other countries in 2019, the last year that the deal was effective.

At the time, NAFTA was the largest free trade agreement on a geographical scale. The deal was signed to boost trade and eliminate barriers between the three countries in order to boost GDP, lower consumer prices, and establish better economic and diplomatic relations.

Following in the footsteps of the EU, which earlier in the year enacted free movement of goods between its member nations, NAFTA eliminated essentially all of the existing tariffs and trade restrictions between the US, Canada, and Mexico.   https://t.co/ajTN8WwSFe
On this day in 1993, Bill Clinton signed NAFTA into law. The deal was first drafted by President Reagan in 1987, who advocated for the idea in his 1980 Presidential campaign.

Of the entire scandal, former CEO Ken Lay said â€œI take full responsibility for what happened at Enron. But saying that, I know in my mind that I did nothing criminal.â€

Layâ€™s oversight of one of the worst corporate scandals in US history earned him a spot near the top of the list of worst CEOs of all-time edging out Jimmy Cayne and  trailing only Angelo Mozilo and Dick Fuld.  https://t.co/wZq2kmOhDX

In response to the Enron scandal, Congress passed the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, which established frequent auditing and extensive financial reporting regulations for publicly traded companies. The purpose of this act was to protect shareholders from bad actors like Enronâ€™s executives.
Financial fraud was not the only illegal act that Enron engaged in. The company essentially created an artificial energy crisis in California which sent prices soaring.

Between 1996 and 2001, Enron was named the most innovative company for six years in a row. In 1999, the company launched the first commodity trading website that was capable of servicing clients across the globe.

Although Enron was a massive scandal, the company was still a pioneer in helping to establish energy derivatives, which through deregulation allowed investors to speculate on energy prices and providers to hedge their assets.

The bankruptcy led to a few notable deaths. While awaiting sentencing, Lay passed away due to cardiac issues. J. Clifford Baxter, Enronâ€™s Vice Chairman, was found dead in an apparent suicide. Many other executives also received jail time.

Interestingly enough, Fortune magazine ranked Enron as the fifth largest US company in 2002, according to CNN. This was after the stock had crashed and the company filed Chapter 11.  https://t.co/fOJ3yU6sBH
Arthur Anderson, an accounting giant of the time, fell as well after the companyâ€™s auditors were found guilty of knowingly covering up the scandal by destroying relevant documents.
Enron hid losses and debts through its subsidiaries, which inflated earnings and completely misrepresented the business to investors. Enron wasnâ€™t the only company to fall, though.

During this crash, CEO Kenneth Lay acted particularly devious, selling as many shares as he could while encouraging employees to buy shares in a reverse Robin Hood scheme. As a result, employees saw their savings accounts disappear.   https://t.co/y7w2343lMp

In 2001, Enron paid $680M to its top 140 executives while simultaneously restricting lower-level employees from selling stock due to 401k restrictions. Clearly, this event was the antithesis of corporate governance.

Before the year 2001, Enron had ranked as the number seven company on the Fortune 500 after posting $111B in revenue in the year 2000 and employing 20,000 people. However, between August 2000 and November 2001, the stock tanked from the low $90â€™s to just 26 cents.

On this day in 2001, Enron filed for Chapter 11 protection, marking one of the largest US scandals in corporate history. Enron operated as an energy trading company and was based out of Houston, Texas.  https://t.co/L3P6UtJJYO

This form of pricing existed for almost 100 years, when computers and electronic displays took precedence. Although ticker tapes have become a relic of the past, the use of tickers themselves will continue to be embedded in the stock market for decades to come.

These tapes gave investors real time information in regards to the price of stocks, which increased the fairness and transparency of the market. The name â€˜tickerâ€™ derived its name from the sound that the type wheel would make while printing prices.

Edward Calahan, who dropped out of school at 11 years old, invented the ticker tape, which was the first electronic method used in the stock market. Essentially, the ticker tape would quote stock prices for investors around the country through the use of morse code.  https://t.co/cGHdaS4tQc

With all other options exhausted, Lehman filed for bankruptcy on 9/15/08 with a reported $639B in assets and $613B in debt making it, at the time and still today, the largest bankruptcy filing in US History.  https://t.co/xWK3oIWBTK

The trajectory of Lehman was going towards extinction. The federal government refused to bail out â€˜yet another bank,â€™ and Treasury Secretary Paulson later commented: "I never once considered that it was appropriate to put taxpayer money on the line in resolving Lehman Brothers."
To help boost its balance sheet, the bank announced plans to raise $6B in capital after reporting its first ever loss as a public company in June 2008.  https://t.co/NIVZMIwSLI

The capital raise announcement didnâ€™t help.  The fall of the legacy bank occurred swiftly. On 9/10/08, the bank declared that it expected to write down $5.6B for toxic assets and would attempt to spin off another $50B into a separate entity.  https://t.co/CTdPaD59kO

Lehmanâ€™s troubles werenâ€™t exactly a surprise.  After Bear Stearns was sold to JP Morgan for $2 per share in a last-minute deal to avoid bankruptcy in March 2008, Lehman was speculated as the potential next domino to fall.

Lehman was especially vulnerable, as they also relied on repurchase agreements to fund their investments. Repurchase agreements occur when an individual sells a government security to buyers with the promise of purchasing them back the next day at a slightly higher price.
What did Lehman do in response?  They doubled down (literally) by more than doubling their Real Estate related holdings, totaling $111B by the end of fiscal year 2007.

But prices did start to fall, and in many cases by a lot.  The result was that holders of mortgage-backed securities and loans saw huge losses, as they were unable to sell the homes for anything close to the price they paid.

Before the crisis, it was always assumed that housing prices never meaningfully dropped in value. Therefore, if a borrower defaulted, the lender could foreclose on the house and recoup the value of the loan.
This was a risky endeavor, which was proven in 2006 when the housing bubble popped. As the value of homes started to decline, many borrowers were unable to make their payments.

Some of these lenders were involved in riskier subprime mortgages which were loans to buyers with weaker credit scores.  By pooling these mortgages together and securitizing them, it was thought that the overall default risk would decline.   https://t.co/KGPAnYyQ0l

Leading up to the crisis, The US rode a housing boom, which led Wall Street firms to get involved with collateral debt obligations and mortgage-backed securities. Lehman Brothers took this a step further, acquiring five mortgage lenders.  https://t.co/UZfdEI0MuH
At the time, Lehman was the fourth largest investment bank and employed 25,000 people. Itâ€™s bankruptcy was the largest in US history and involved $639 billion in assets.  https://t.co/ayTQFXyR7A
